-- 
Indian Stocks Decline on Speculation Fuel Prices May Increase

-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w   a n d   S h i k h a r   B a l w a n i
-- 
2011-05-10T11:40:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-10/indian-stocks-climb-hindalco-unilever-lead-gains-on-earnings.html
Indian shares retreated for the first
time in three days amid speculation that the government may
increase fuel prices, stoking inflation and triggering a further
tightening of interest rates.  Mahindra & Mahindra Ltd. (MM) , the country’s biggest maker of
sports-utility vehicles and tractors, lost 1.5 percent.  HDFC
Bank Ltd. (HDFCB) , the third-biggest lender, slid 1.4 percent. India’s
government may raise prices of gasoline by 2.5 rupees a liter,
Bloomberg UTV reported today, citing oil ministry sources it
didn’t identify. The ministry has recommended raising diesel
prices too, the report said.  Reserve Bank  of India Governor
Duvvuri Subbarao said in  Basel ,  Switzerland  yesterday the
central bank should continue with its “anti-inflationary
stance” even if that meant sacrificing some economic growth in
the short term.  “A hike in diesel prices is on the cards; the question is
the quantum,” Mehraboon Jamshed Irani, head of private client
group at Nirmal Bang Securities Pvt. in Mumbai, said by phone.
“Markets are not going up as the pace of economic growth is
likely to slow. It’s time to move to the defensive sectors and
dividend-yielding stocks.”  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, slid
16.19, or 0.1 percent, to 18,512.77 at the 3:30 p.m. close in
Mumbai. The S&P CNX Nifty Index on the National Stock Exchange
dropped 0.2 percent to 5,541.25. Its May futures settled at
5,545.80. The BSE 200 Index lost 0.1 percent to 2,286.11.  The Sensex has declined 9.7 percent this year on concern
higher borrowing costs will hurt corporate earnings. Sensex
stocks trade at an average 14.7 times estimated profit, down
from 21.5 times in March 2010. The MSCI Emerging Markets Index
is valued at 11.3 times.  Interest Rates   Earnings growth in India for the quarter ended March has
trailed year-earlier levels or missed analysts’ estimates for 9
of the 16 Sensex companies that have reported results so far,
data compiled by Bloomberg show.  The oil ministry recommended an increase of 3 rupees to 4
rupees a liter in the price of diesel and proposed raising the
cost of cooking gas, the Bloomberg UTV report said. A meeting of
a ministerial panel to consider raising fuel prices has been
deferred to May 17 or May 18, Oil minister S. Jaipal Reddy said
in  New Delhi  today.  The nation’s central bank has increased rates nine times
since last March. Governor Subbarao on May 3 said inflation will
stay “elevated” until September, and forecast that the South
Asian economy may expand about 8 percent in the year to March
31, from 8.6 percent in the previous year.  Automakers Drop  Mahindra dropped for a second day, losing 1.5 percent to
699.6 rupees, while motorcycle maker  Hero Honda Motors Ltd. (HH) 
dropped 1.7 percent to 1,713.9 rupees.  HDFC Bank fell 1.4 percent to 2,246.4 rupees.  ICICI Bank
Ltd. (ICICIBC) , the country’s second-biggest lender, slid 0.6 percent to
1,076.2 rupees.  Tata Steel Ltd. (TATA) , the largest producer of the
alloy, lost 1.1 percent to 588.4 rupees.  NTPC Ltd. (NATP)  climbed 4.5 percent to 180.55 rupees, the most in
more than two months, after the largest power producer posted
fourth-quarter net income of 27.8 billion rupees today,
exceeding the 25.5 billion rupee forecast in the Bloomberg
survey of analysts.  Hindustan Unilever Ltd. (HUVR) , the nation’s largest consumer
goods maker, rallied 4.4 percent to 297.25 rupees, the most
since Oct. 21. Kotak Institutional Equities today raised its
recommendation on the stock to “add,” from “sell,” while
Emkay Global Financial Services Ltd. lifted its rating to
“accumulate” from “hold.” The Indian unit of Unilever Plc
yesterday posted fourth-quarter profit that exceeded analysts’
estimates, pushing the stock 3.2 percent higher.  Overseas investors bought a net 2.44 billion rupees ($54.5
million) of Indian stocks on May 9, taking their investments in
equities this year to 18.5 billion rupees, according to data on
the  website  of the Securities and Exchange Board of  India .  India’s economic expansion and corporate profits lured
foreign funds to buy a record $29.4 billion of local equities
last year and made the Sensex the best performer and most
expensive among the world’s 10 biggest markets.  To contact the reporter on this story:
